Anonymous Thu 21 Mar 2019 12:26:51 No.22015820 Report

>>22015706
Humans reach sexual maturity around 15, though, so even with a life expectancy of 40 that gives plenty of years for reproduction and - more crucially - ensuring the next generation live to see sexual maturity. On top of that, a not insignificant reason as to why life expectancy was so low in the past is because of high infant mortality rates and lots of murder. You could absolutely live to see 80; it just required more luck.

For a species to die naturally at around 13 years of age despite access to modern medicine, etc., after reaching sexual maturity at around 8 (pure estimation based on the image), would be a recipe for extinction. How would protect the young until they reach sexual maturity, if their parents are extremely likely to die before that? The reason so many animals can fend for themselves hours after birth is because it's necessary to ensure the species doesn't go extinct. I could buy a 30-ish year life span (a la that one species in Mass Effect), but less than 15? No.
